<ArticleLayout
  title="Kitchen Drawers That Are Easier to Use"
  description="Before buying kitchen drawer organisers, check drawer depth, width, height, utensil sizes, daily habits and whether dividers will actually make the drawer easier to use."
  category="Kitchen"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="7 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with timber cabinetry, green accents and tidy drawer storage"
>
  <p>
    Kitchen drawers can become frustrating quickly. Cutlery shifts around. Utensils tangle
    together. Measuring spoons disappear. Lunchbox parts, wraps, food bags and small tools get
    pushed to the back.
  </p>
  <p>
    In many kitchens, the drawer is not too small. It is simply being asked to handle too many
    jobs: cooking, packing lunches, baking, storing takeaway extras and catching whatever does
    not have another home.
  </p>
  <p>
    A drawer organiser should make the drawer easier to use every day. It should not just make
    the drawer look tidy for a few minutes after it has been rearranged.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader kitchen storage planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/best-kitchen-storage-ideas-small-australian-homes/">Kitchen Storage That Makes Small Cupboards Easier to Use</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>What keeps going wrong in the drawer?</h2>
  <p>Start by identifying the actual issue rather than choosing an insert first.</p>
  <p>A kitchen drawer may be difficult to use because:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>There are too many utensils in one drawer.</li>
    <li>Cutlery is mixed with cooking tools.</li>
    <li>The drawer is too shallow for bulky items.</li>
    <li>Long utensils sit diagonally and waste space.</li>
    <li>Measuring spoons and small tools fall underneath larger items.</li>
    <li>The drawer organiser does not fit properly.</li>
    <li>Items are stored far from where they are used.</li>
    <li>Duplicate tools are taking up space.</li>
    <li>The drawer has become a dumping ground.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A cluttered utensil drawer needs a different answer from a drawer that is too shallow,
    too narrow or filled with the wrong items.
  </p>
  <p>
    If cutlery is sliding around, a cutlery tray may help. If long utensils are tangled, a
    wider utensil organiser may help. If the drawer contains too many rarely used tools,
    buying another insert may not solve the problem.
  </p>
  <p>
    Decide what the drawer should actually do, then choose an organiser only if it supports
    that job.
  </p>

  <h2>Give the drawer one main job</h2>
  <p>
    A drawer works better when it has a clear purpose.
  </p>
  <p>Common kitchen drawer jobs include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Everyday cutlery.</li>
    <li>Cooking utensils.</li>
    <li>Knives and food preparation tools.</li>
    <li>Measuring spoons and baking tools.</li>
    <li>Wraps, foil and food bags.</li>
    <li>Tea towels and cloths.</li>
    <li>Small appliance accessories.</li>
    <li>Lunchbox parts and lids.</li>
    <li>Miscellaneous household items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some drawers can handle more than one category, but only if the items are used together
    and fit comfortably.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, wraps, foil and food bags may work well together. Cutlery and large cooking
    utensils usually do not. Tea towels and sharp tools should not be mixed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying an organiser, decide which items belong in the drawer and which should move
    elsewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the actual interior</h2>
  <p>
    Drawer organisers often fail because the outside measurements of the drawer are used
    instead of the internal usable space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure inside the drawer.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Internal width.</li>
    <li>Internal depth.</li>
    <li>Internal height.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer sides curve inward.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer base has raised edges.</li>
    <li>Whether screws, runners or fittings reduce usable space.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer closes fully with the organiser inside.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A product may technically fit across the top of the drawer but still catch on the drawer
    frame when opening or closing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the actual usable space, not the cabinet front.
  </p>

  <h2>Leave enough height for the drawer to close</h2>
  <p>
    Drawer height is easy to overlook.
  </p>
  <p>
    A shallow drawer may not suit bulky utensil organisers, stacked tools, deep trays or
    lidded storage inserts.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check the height of:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The drawer interior.</li>
    <li>The organiser.</li>
    <li>The tallest utensil or item.</li>
    <li>Any handles that sit upward.</li>
    <li>Stacked tools such as measuring cups.</li>
    <li>Knife guards or blade covers.</li>
    <li>Rolling pins or bulky gadgets.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The drawer needs enough clearance to close without scraping.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the drawer already struggles to close, the problem may be item selection rather than
    the lack of an organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Use the longest utensil as the test</h2>
  <p>
    Long utensils are one of the main reasons kitchen drawers become messy.
  </p>
  <p>Measure the longest items you want to store, such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Spatulas.</li>
    <li>Tongs.</li>
    <li>Wooden spoons.</li>
    <li>Ladles.</li>
    <li>Whisks.</li>
    <li>Rolling pins.</li>
    <li>Barbecue tools.</li>
    <li>Serving spoons.</li>
    <li>Large knives in sheaths.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Then compare those lengths with the drawer depth and the organiser compartments.
  </p>
  <p>
    If long utensils only fit diagonally, they may waste space and block other items. In that
    case, a wider drawer, upright utensil holder, wall rail or separate storage location may
    work better.
  </p>
  <p>
    An organiser cannot fix a drawer that is too short for the items being stored.
  </p>

  <h2>Will the compartments hold what you own?</h2>
  <p>
    Not all drawer organisers suit the same items.
  </p>
  <p>
    A standard cutlery tray may work for forks, knives, spoons and teaspoons. It may not work
    for cooking utensils, peelers, tongs or measuring cups.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Compartment length.</li>
    <li>Compartment width.</li>
    <li>Compartment depth.</li>
    <li>Whether utensils can be lifted out easily.</li>
    <li>Whether small items will get trapped underneath larger ones.</li>
    <li>Whether the organiser wastes space around the edges.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Expandable organisers can help, but they still need enough drawer width and depth to
    expand properly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume an expandable organiser will suit every drawer.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove duplicates before shopping</h2>
  <p>
    Many kitchen drawers need editing before they need organising.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying a new insert, remove everything from the drawer and group similar items
    together.
  </p>
  <p>Look for duplicates such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Multiple peelers.</li>
    <li>Extra spatulas.</li>
    <li>Unused bottle openers.</li>
    <li>Several measuring spoon sets.</li>
    <li>Duplicate tongs.</li>
    <li>Old takeaway cutlery.</li>
    <li>Broken clips.</li>
    <li>Random appliance parts.</li>
    <li>Tools kept just in case.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If an item is not used, does not work properly, or belongs to an appliance you no longer
    own, it probably does not need prime drawer space.
  </p>
  <p>
    A smaller number of useful tools will usually work better than a crowded drawer with a new
    organiser added.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose for the drawer, not the packaging</h2>
  <p>
    Different drawer organisers suit different problems.
  </p>

  <h3>Cutlery trays</h3>
  <p>
    Cutlery trays are useful for everyday forks, knives, spoons and teaspoons.
  </p>
  <p>
    They work best when the drawer is close to where meals are served or where dishes are
    unloaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check the tray length, width and height. Also check whether the
    compartments suit the amount of cutlery in the household.
  </p>
  <p>
    A tray that is too small will overflow. A tray that is too large may waste valuable drawer
    space.
  </p>

  <h3>Expandable drawer organisers</h3>
  <p>
    Expandable organisers can suit drawers with unusual widths.
  </p>
  <p>
    They are useful when you want a closer fit than a fixed-size tray provides.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the minimum and maximum expanded width before buying. Some expandable organisers
    also become less stable when fully extended, especially if heavy tools are stored in the
    outer sections.
  </p>

  <h3>Bamboo or timber dividers</h3>
  <p>
    Bamboo and timber organisers can look tidy and suit many kitchens.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check whether the material is sealed or easy to clean. Kitchen drawers can collect crumbs,
    oil and dust, so smooth wipeable surfaces are usually easier to maintain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Timber-style organisers may not suit damp areas or drawers that regularly hold wet tools.
  </p>

  <h3>Adjustable dividers</h3>
  <p>
    Adjustable dividers can be useful for creating custom sections.
  </p>
  <p>
    They work well when the drawer contains items of different sizes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check how the dividers are held in place. Some tension dividers need strong
    side pressure and may not suit every drawer. Others may slide around if the drawer is
    opened quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>Small-item trays</h3>
  <p>
    Small trays can help with measuring spoons, clips, bag ties, corn holders, bottle openers
    and other small items.
  </p>
  <p>
    They are useful when small pieces disappear underneath larger utensils.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid making too many tiny categories. If the system becomes fiddly, it may be difficult
    to maintain.
  </p>

  <h2>Location changes what belongs there</h2>
  <p>
    Storage should match how the kitchen is used.
  </p>
  <p>
    A cutlery drawer is usually most useful near the dishwasher, sink, dining area or plate
    storage. Cooking utensils are usually more useful near the stove or main preparation area.
    Wraps and bags may work better near the fridge, pantry or lunchbox area.
  </p>
  <p>Before reorganising drawers, ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where do I use these items?</li>
    <li>Where do I put them away after washing?</li>
    <li>Who uses this drawer most often?</li>
    <li>Is the drawer easy to reach?</li>
    <li>Are sharp items stored safely?</li>
    <li>Are heavy items stored low enough?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A drawer in the right place can reduce movement around the kitchen.
  </p>

  <h2>If you rent or the kitchen is small</h2>
  <p>
    Renters and small-kitchen households usually benefit from non-permanent drawer storage.
  </p>
  <p>Useful options may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Removable cutlery trays.</li>
    <li>Adjustable dividers.</li>
    <li>Shallow trays.</li>
    <li>Stackable small containers.</li>
    <li>Drawer boxes that can move between homes.</li>
    <li>Non-adhesive inserts.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid permanent modifications unless you own the kitchen or have approval.
  </p>
  <p>
    For very small kitchens, focus on the tools used most often. Store occasional items
    somewhere else, such as a higher cupboard, storage tub or utility area.
  </p>
  <p>
    Trying to keep every kitchen item in one small drawer usually makes the drawer harder to
    use.
  </p>

  <h2>Where drawer organisers fail</h2>
  <p>
    Kitchen drawer storage can become frustrating when the organiser is chosen before the
    drawer is understood.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying an organiser before measuring the drawer.</li>
    <li>Ignoring drawer height.</li>
    <li>Keeping too many duplicate tools.</li>
    <li>Mixing unrelated categories.</li>
    <li>Storing long utensils in drawers that are too short.</li>
    <li>Choosing compartments that do not fit actual utensils.</li>
    <li>Using deep trays in shallow drawers.</li>
    <li>Storing sharp tools loosely.</li>
    <li>Filling every section too tightly.</li>
    <li>Buying an organiser that is hard to clean.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A useful drawer setup is easy to open, use and reset. Empty compartments matter less than
    being able to find daily tools quickly.
  </p>

  <h2>When dividers will not fix the drawer</h2>
  <p>
    Hold off on buying a new drawer organiser if the real issue is clutter.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check whether the drawer contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Broken tools.</li>
    <li>Unused gadgets.</li>
    <li>Duplicate utensils.</li>
    <li>Appliance parts with no clear purpose.</li>
    <li>Takeaway items.</li>
    <li>Loose packaging.</li>
    <li>Items that belong in another room.</li>
    <li>Tools kept only because they came in a set.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If removing these items solves the problem, a new organiser may not be necessary.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sometimes the best drawer upgrade is simply giving the drawer one clear job.
  </p>

  <h2>Measurements to note</h2>
  <p>Before buying a kitchen drawer organiser, measure and check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Internal drawer width.</li>
    <li>Internal drawer depth.</li>
    <li>Internal drawer height.</li>
    <li>Drawer side shape.</li>
    <li>Organiser height.</li>
    <li>Utensil length.</li>
    <li>Compartment size.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer closes properly.</li>
    <li>Whether items can be lifted out easily.</li>
    <li>Whether the organiser is easy to clean.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer has one clear purpose.</li>
    <li>Whether duplicate items can be removed first.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Kitchen drawer storage works best when it is simple, measured and matched to daily use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start by removing what does not belong, then give the drawer one clear job. If the weekly
    tools are easier to grab and put away, the setup is working.
  </p>
  <p>
    For pantry-specific storage planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/pantry-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">Pantry Storage That Fits Your Shelves</a>.
  </p>

